Weber Grill family donates $10 million to U of C neonatal unit


The family that founded the Weber Grill donated $10 million to the University of Chicago hospital's neonatal-care unit.“We got to know David Gozal, who heads the neonatal unit and learned about his vision to really help these young lives,” Jim Stephen, chairman of Palatine-based Weber-Stephen Products Co., told me yesterday before news of the big donation was announced.Mr. Stephen, his nine siblings, mother, Marge Stephen, and a niece each donated about $800,000 to come up with the donation. The neonatology center's new name is the Margaret M. and George A. Stephen Neonatal Intensive Care Unit (NICU), named in honor of Mr. Stephen's father, who died in 1993.Weber-Stephen Products was acquired by BDT Capital Partners LLC three years ago, though Mr. Stephen's family still runs the grill-making company.The family's gift will support research into treatments for premature newborns and genetic studies of childhood diseases. The donation also enables the hospital to hire a neonatologist who will become the new Stephen Family Professor of Pediatrics, the hospital said in a statement.Mr. Stephen told me the gift's origins began more than a decade ago when he and his family first learned about the work being done at the hospital. Then the family started taking part in a picnic at the hospital.“We're in the barbecue business so we thought we'd help with the picnic,” he said.That participation grew into serious discussions among family members to donate, said Mr. Stephen, adding it was his sister, Barb Rapp, who organized the effort.


BDT Capital Partners LLC
University of Chicago
Weber-Stephen Products LLC



























